review_blob: On Draught,Clear and amber in color, thick head reduces to a creamy layer.Huge English hop aroma, some citrus and pine needles. Medium body is crisp and finishing bitter. Overpowered by hops in flavor which leave a lingering bitterness. Some sweetness, some grains involved. overall a super hoppy brew.

330cl Bottle Pour is hazy and reddish looking very christmas and with an initially frothy head which settled down to a light layer of froth. The aroma of cinnamon and oak also play the holiday part. Sweet flavor and sticky with holiday spices, yeast and oak. Creamy body, very nicely done!

750ml Bottled in 2010. Ive had this cellared for about 15 months. Black and dark as night with a lasting kahki head. Nice choco roasted malts in aroma, licorice and faint herbal. Full bodied and smooth, slight oily and slight dry finish with some bitter chocolate. Flavor is really nice on this one. Cocoa, roasted smoky malts, licorice and the honey is faint in the finish addding an additional fine quality. Overall I would say this is the best of the DFH experimental brews Ive had. A really nice Impy.

22oz Bottle from Wine & Cheese Place. Crystal clear copper color with a short head. Incredible hop aroma, mostly citrus and floral some pine and bubblegum, not unlike Dreadnaught. Reminds me of fresh Dread. Medium body, syrupy and slick leaving a sharp bitterness. Flavor is real fruity, tangerine and grapefruit come to mind with some nice underlying malt. Overall a real quality brew!

500ML Bottle. Hazy golden color sizable head, some decent retention. Citrusy hop aroma, tangerine. Body is medium and smooth, dry finish. flavor has nice nice oak notes and tha hops give an orange like note. Drinks easily, was hoping it would be better. Overal an ok IPA but pricey at $7.99.
UPDATED: AUG 13, 2014

33cl Bottle from Wine and Cheese Place. Cloudy amber/brown in color small creamy tan head. Candy sugar, dried fruits, malt slightly vinous. Creamy medium body slick a bit oily. light hop bitterness. Fruity malty flavor, caramel, cherries. Overall a nice but not over the top Belgian

750ml bottle, Cloudy and a darker golden with some scattered lacing. Floral, grassy hoppy aroma, yeast. Medium bodied some dryness in finish. Somewhat bitter tasting, some light sweetness and fruit. Overall very average. Last pour produced heavy sediment and its bitterness.

750ml Bottle. Really nice Saison. Golden and slightly cloudy with a beautiful white head.  Really nice aromas of fruit, pineapple , yeasty Bretts and spices and florals. Creamy mouthfeel lightly dry bitter finish. Nice use of hops. Flavor is straightforward Saison.  Tangy, spicy and tart nice hop bitterness. Overall really nice one!

330ml Bottle. I cant believe I haven;t rated this before Ive had it so many times over the years. A beautiful golden color with a slight haze and a short creamy head. Aroma is spicy and fruity with nice yeast and clove notes. Body is medium, smooth with some creaminess. Light peppery bitterness in finish, slightly dry. Nice flavor with some spicy notes, clove again, slight sweetness. Overall reall balanced and well made. Yeast reminds me on La Fin Du  Monde from Uni.
On draught, Dark and oily looking, no head. Butterscotch bomb aroma. Oily medium body. Really sweeeeet, butterscotch, vanilla light hop bitternes. Really too sweet for me. Cloyingly so.
beer_name: Southern Tier Blackwater Series: Creme Brulee Stout

review_blob: On draught at WOB,  Pitch black with a creamy khaki  film.  Amazing chocolate aroma, milk chocolate , cocoa nibs  and roasted malts. Creamy full body. slightly dry finish. Bitter chocolate flavors, hints of  vanilla and  espresso. Nice balance of chocolate and malts . Really nice one.

On draught at Bistro 41 Ft. Myers. Poured in an Affligem chalice. Cloudy and honey colored with a white creamy head. Light hop aroma, some yeast, straw and spice. Creamy body. Spicy peppery a little fruit and yeast in flavor. Overall an excellent Belgian!

On draught at WOB. Dark brown with a light kahki layer of foam. Smoky aroma with notes of Jack Daniels, vanilla, smoke, oak.  Body is a bit oily and slick with a bit of heat at the end. Flavor dominated by smoke, coffee and whiskey. Overall pretty decent.
beer_name: Red Brick Vanilla Gorilla, Jack Barrel Aged

review_blob: 12 oz. bottled, labeled 10588 PKGD 8/12/11 A. Must be pretty fresh. Clear copper pour with a 2 foamy head which retains well leaving lacing throughout. Beautiful job with the dry hopping, very full aromas of pine and tropical fruit. Body is medium oily and slick with a velvety mouthfeel and a lingering bitterness. Flavor gives no way to malt, this is mostly a hop bomb as advertised. Fruity and bitter. Almost too bitter but still an enjoyable one.
22 oz Bottle. Hazy light gold with a typical snow white head. Some lemon and citrus in aroma, bitter and yeasty. Big coriander boost only too bitter for the style.

750ml Bottle corked. Impressive looking beer, lemondrop color and cloudy with a beautiful white head which retains. Unfortunately, this is where the love ends for me. Way too much oak in the way of this being decent in my opinion. The oak really spoils the whole thing for me and cant see how this could be so highly rated. Aromas of oak, yeast some brett and faint citrus. Smooth body and easily drinkable. Flavor again with the oak, some doughy yeast. Overall not my cup of tea.

12oz Bottle. Clear gold with a nice white head. Looks nice. Really not much for aroma, some malty grains, light hops. Flavor is a bit sweet for a lager but Ill run with it. Medium to light body, Overall nothing to remember except refreshing and quite drinkable.

Draught at The Ice House Pub in Punta Gorda. I was amazed at how good this was. Poured into a snifter, golden and slightly hazy with a beautiful white head and good retention. Awsome araomas of spice, citrus, yeast, white pepper and grass. Well rounded mouthfeel finishing quite bitter and dry. Very Belgian, amazed this was brewed in CA. Flavor is typical Belgian saison, lighty sweet, citrus, yeasty and  a bit grassy and earthy. Overall the best Saison Ive ever had on draught here.

750ml Bottle capped and corked. Dark golden in color, cloudy from yeast sediment with a beautiful white head.  Spicy yet hoppy aroma, some peppery notes as well as yeast. Body is well carbonated yet balanced. Bitter yes but not overly stated in my opinion. This is a really nice Saison/Tripel yet leaning sweet with notes of honey and finishing slightly dry. Overall an above average brew and another great offering from Fantome!

22oz Bottle cellared for about a year. Dark cocoa colored and clear with just a whispy layer of foam. Not completely opaque, can see some light making its way through. Aroams of coffee, chocolate and cigarette ash. Maybe a hint of anise or licorice. Oily body, medium to full with low carbonation and avery soft mouthfeel. Some bitterness in the finish, only slightly dry.  Was expecting it to be heavy coffee but am pleasantly surprised that is has some sweet chocolate in there along with some dark roastiness. Should have known, Blue Mountain is a super smooth bean. Overall a really nice Stout!
beer_name: Southern Tier Jah-va Imperial Coffee Stout

review_blob: 33cl Bottle. Like a dark ruby red when held to light with a creamy head. Some fruit and hops in the aroma along with some cocoa or chocolate. Body is pretty full and drinking like a Belgian Strong yet there are some nice roasted and chocolate notes along with a hint of cherry. Later reminds me of Yoo-Hoo at bthe end. Go figure. Lacing is scant, really not much of a stout but more a hybrid Belgian/Stout. Overall enjoyable.

33cl Bottle Bright red with some pinkish foam. An amazing aroma of fresh raspberries here. Nice balance of sweet and tart. High carbonation, medium bodied a bit syrupy as well. Overall one of the better ones Ive tried.

33cl Bottle. Reddish, slightly hazy no head involved. Weak on everything from aroma, body and flavor. Sweet and tart, yet really lacks flavor. Body too watery. Comparing this to some better of the same style.

33cl Bottle. Pours a cloudy deep pink in color with just a bit of bubbles on top.
Huge raspberry aroma, very pleasant. Sweet and tart, more sweet nice fruit flavor. Soda like mouthfeel, a bit syrupy substantial body. Overall a decent one yet not as nice as the St. louis or Lindemans.

12oz Bottle Hazy straw color no head just a light layer of white. Nice aroma of clove and yeast. Body is a bit watery with low carbonation. Some citrus and yeast in the flavor with light hop bitterness in the finish. Overall a bit average.
12oz Botle. Cloudy orange, honey melon and some yeast. Syrupy body, sweet a bit cloying. Overall an amped up sweet wheat.

750ml Nice looking beer, faint cloudiness and golden yellow with an impressive white head that stands quite awhile. peppery spicy nose with light citrus, yeast, some grassiness and a faint funk. Quite hoppy, even amount of bitterness with a creamy mouthfeel and finishing dry. Lightly sweet and spicy, a real nice Tripel!

12oz Bottle. Pours a very cloudy muddy golden color with no head. Some banana in the aroma, kind of weak. Body is medium and carbonation is a bit low. Finding some yeast and wheat in the flavor this is also lacking. Overall, tastes kind of home-brewy.

12oz Bottle, Unusual appearance, butterscotch in color and extremely cloudy and unfiltered looking. Very minimul swirl laying on top. Aroma is perfumy with sweet tropical fruit, pineapple. Body is medium and well carbonated, leaving a slight puckering dry finish. Flavor is tart with fruit, again getting some pinapple and yeast. Overall an interesting brew.

12oz Bottle. Pours a murky cocoa brown with a fine layer of foam floating around. Aroma is mostly yeast and faint roasted malt. Body is  a bit watery with low carbonation. Flavor is a bit weak, lightly sweet a hint of clove. Overall weak for the style. Not impressed.

12oz Bottle.A cloudy golden pour yielding a fluffy white head which settles down quickly. Aromas of wheat, yeast, clove and a faint smokiness. Smells every bit as a German Weiss. Medium body is creamy with just the right amount of carbonation. Flavor also very German. Wheat malt, yeast, clove and slightly sweet. Overall another amazing brew from NG!

12oz bottle, hazy and a glowing golden in color. Beautiful head settleng down slowly and retaining well, nice lacing. Really nice aromas, citrus, yeast, wonderful clove, lemon and hops. Alot going on here, really complex with layer after layer of wakening my senses. Body is creamy and smooth, just the right amount of bitterness finishing slightly dry. The flavor is also amazing with wheat malts, pepper, fruity citrus and yeast. I;ve been wondering how this beer had ranked so high in its style for quite some time and now I can see it is well deserved in its ranking. Overall an unbelievable brew! Thanks Brandon!
beer_name: New Glarus Thumbprint Series Imperial Weizen

review_blob: On Draught,  Clear brown, quite light for the style. Aromas of coffee, cherries and tobacco. Light body for the style. Coffee flavors, smoky and faint fruit. Overall very weak for the style.
beer_name: Blue Point Sour Cherry Imperial Stout

review_blob: 22oz Bomber A cloudy amber/orange pour with a short dense and lasting head. Reminds me of Brutal Bitter in appearance. Hoppy biscuity aroma with fruity overtones, pine and bubblegum. Oily body, slick with a fairly bitter bite in the finish. Hoppy somewhat sweet in flavor. Willamette really the star here. Overall a nicely done hoppy Ale.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: 12oz Bottle. Reddish brown in color with very little head. Sweet malt and cardboard aroma. Thin body, light bitterness. Flavor is malty sweet, faint hops. Washes down wings well.

On Draught at South Street served in a snifter. A slightly cloudy amber with light lacing that retains well. Sweet fruit in the aroma along with citrus, sugary bubblegum and piney hops. Medium body which is low on carbonation and oily slick, A slight numbing bitterness lingers and lingers. The flavor is sweet sweet hops, some peach and again sugary bubblegum. Overall better than I expected.
On Draught.  Is this beer? Golden orange in color with a slight haze. Immediately struck by the orange aroma. Fizzy and very much like orange soda. Super sweet and I can only taste orange, Yuk!

On draught.Clear copper in color with light lacing. Citrusy hoppy aroma, weak body slightly watery with light carbonation.  Light bitterness in finish with notes of tangerine. Overall refreshing and lightt all the way around.

12oz Bottle., Pours a hazy pale gold with no head. Honey and a bit of clove hit me. Medium bodied with very low carbonation. Flavor is really sweet, maybe from the honey I guess. Some yeast and clove in the flavor. Lingering honey notes. Overall a failure in my opinion.

12oz Bottle Best By March 30,2012. Pale straw in color and slightly cloudy with a short dense white head. Nice aroma of citrus, Yeast and lemon. soft mouthfeel, slightly dry. Flavor is sweet and spices are muted. Overall not bad but not really on point for a Wit.

500ml bottle NO DATE CODE. Apparently they give a freshness date on German sold bottles but for us in the US. Anyway, a dark golden with a thick white head which doesnt last very long. Citrus, white pepper and yeast in the aroma with some faint spicy notes. Medium bodied with a low carbonation and slightly slick finish. Flavor is on the sweet side, with some fruit and light bitterness. Not sure how fresh this one is but Im guessing its not. Really would like to see some decipherable date coding on these bottles.

On draught at the Icehouse Pub PG. Slightly hazy pale golden. minimum lacing. Light body yet slightly creamy and finishing dry. Spicy aroma, pepper, orange, citrus. Some bitterness I usually dont find in the style.  Refreshing yet not as good as others Ive had. A bit too much citrus in the flavor.
beer_name: Cigar City Florida Cracker White Ale

review_blob: 500ml Bottle. Pale golden and cloudy with a thick white head. Huge blast of clove along with yeast and citrus. Medium bodied and effervescent. Flavor is sweeter than a regular Hefe and here is the difference. Overall, really nice brew. Like a Hefe but stronger and sweeter.
750ml. Hazy medium gold color with a dense white head. Lots of hops in aroma, funky yeast and fruity. Super creamy mouthfeel. Somewhat sweet in flavor, yeast, floralmamd grassy.

12OZ Bottle. Slightly hazy and brown with a short dense head. Nice mouthfeel, soft carbonation and slightly creamy. Oatmeal and cinnamon in the aroma, tastes very much like a good brown ale with the addition of the oatmeal. Not getting much raisin though.
beer_name: Cigar City Oatmeal Raisin Cookie Brown Ale

review_blob: 750ml. Pours espresso on color wiyh a creamy lasting head, Nice looking beer! Aroma of roasted malts, chocolate and spices.  A hint of licorice and cinnamon. Body is creamy and a little slick. Flavor is on the sweet side with coffee, chocolate and some subtle spices. a hint of brett in the finish. Overall not bad but not as good as some of my favorite Xmas ales

12oz Bottle. Appearance similar to the regular Jai Alaiazy orange in color with a short thick head. Aroma heavy on the oak, big turn off. Also ruins the fruity flavor of the original. Medium bodied and less oily. What a let down.
beer_name: Cigar City White Oak Jai Alai India Pale Ale

review_blob: 22oz Bottle. Pours a cloudy apple cider color with a short thick head. Fruity aroma with plenty of hops and bread dough. Oily medium body which is soft with lower carbonation. Bitter and hoppy with notes of plums and caramel. Overall a nice BW
Clear copper with a creamy head and decent lacing. Piney hops and bubblegum aromas. Oily and low carbonation, lacks acidity. Sweet hoppy flavor, one dimensional.
beer_name: Terrapin So Fresh & So Green Green 2010 (Amarillo)
